Democratic Alliance leader Mmusi Maimane is expected to launch a national petition in Soshanguve in Gauteng on Saturday to oppose the one percent VAT (value added tax) increase announced in the budget in Parliament this week. Finance Minister Malusi Gigaba announced in his maiden budget speech on Wednesday that value added tax would increase from 14 to 15 percent. Maimane said the increase would have a negative impact on the poor and the unemployed. "The increase of VAT, along with a huge increase in fuel levies, will cause an increase in food and transport costs for all South Africans.  The increase of VAT, along with a huge increase in fuel levies, will cause an increase in food and transport costs for all South Africans. We cannot allow ANC government to force poor South Africans to pay for their looting of public money.#NoToVATincreases  â€” Democratic Alliance (@Our_DA) February 24, 2018  "The ANC cannot make the poor pay for their looting of public money," he said in a statement. Maimane will be joined at the launch by DA Gauteng leader John Moodey and City of Tshwane mayor Solly Msimanga. African News Agency (ANA)